    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-06T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-06T06:00:00-05:00" n="259"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d259">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4027: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-06T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 6, 1932—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following telegram has been sent to Shanghai:</p>
                <p>February 6, 7 p.m. Please communicate the following to <persName
                        corresp="#p_TAMM1">Admiral Taylor</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“British Admiral informed British Minister Friday<note n="73"
                                xml:id="d259fn73">February 5.</note> that he had seen the Japanese
                            admiral who agreed that he (the Japanese admiral) would withdraw within
                            the line of Settlement which includes salient of Hongkew Park if the
                            Chinese will evacuate Chapei and Pao[shan?] behind line approximately
                            joining north bend Soochow Creek in Settlement and Sikh crematory and
                            sewage treatment works just north of Hongkew. Area evacuated to be
                            occupied by international troops.</p>
                        <p>British Minister has shown this suggestion to <persName corresp="#p_LW1"
                                >Lo Wen-kan</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CM1">Chen
                                Ming-shu</persName> who agree in principle provided it does not
                            imply 1900 [<hi rend="italic">1901</hi>] protocol<note n="74"
                                xml:id="d259fn74">Signed at Peking, September 7, 1901, <ref
                                    target="frus1901China#pg_312">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1901, Appendix
                                    (Affairs in China), p. 312</ref>.</note> terms or principles at
                            Shanghai and that it is only a temporary arrangement. They will discuss
                            proposal in detail and inform <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1">Sir
                                Miles</persName> tonight whether they are ready to instruct Chinese
                            general at Shanghai and Mayor of Shanghai to negotiate on these terms. I
                            hear you will cooperate with British commander in chief in his efforts
                            to bring about cessation of hostilities and restoration of peaceful
                            conduct at Shanghai.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
